            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_105wh' title='Col. 105WH &mdash; HC Deb 20 December 2000 vol 360 c105WH' name='column_105wh' href='#column_105wh' rel='bookmark'>105WH</a>
            the fee cut in 1992, rather than the contract itself. If I may, I shall say something later about what I think is the appropriate balance between capitation-based payments and fee-for-service-based payments, and how we might expect NHS dentistry to develop in future.</p><p>
            The hon. Member for South Swindon also talked about the Government's commitment to restoring NHS dentistry, and explained the baseline for that assessment. Whatever that commitment might be, it is not, however, to restore the general dental service model. In constant terms, spending on general dental services will be lower this year than in 1992&#x2013;93. Of course, I acknowledge that there are additional expenditure items outside general dental services, and I shall return in a moment to the balance between GDS and other methods of providing NHS dentistry.
          </p>
